North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions would deepen their mistrust of the United States and the country would not unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the World Organization that last year North Korea had taken “substantial measures of good will”; for example, it had stopped nuclear and missile tests, dismantled the nuclear test site and pledged not to multiply nuclear weapons and technologies.
“But we don’t see a corresponding reaction from the US,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there is no trust in our national security, and under these circumstances we will in no way disarm unilaterally first.”
While Ri repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, where North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the Korean War from 1950 to 1953, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes demands for easing strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'first denuclearization' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and is even opposed to 'declaring the end of the war,'" Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us to our knees is a ghost of people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our suspicion.”
Ri did not address plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US head of state had highlighted earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party on the denuclearization issue instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a standstill.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ris’ speech differed tremendously from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to use North Korea’s missiles to target the US mainland after “bad President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea’s “total destruction,” overwhelmed Kim with praise at the United Nations for his courage in terms of disarmament steps, but said much work remains to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he has no time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, however, told the UN Security Council on Thursday, “The enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must in any case be continued vigorously until we have achieved complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 to financially dry up Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was unsuccessful.
In July, when he left Pyongyang, he said that progress had been made only to be accused hours later by North Korea of making “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea vowed at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile base and a nuclear complex if the United States took “corresponding measures”.
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" sought were security guarantees Trump had given in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Learn to Sleep Enough in a Course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year, a measure against the spreading macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often needless when it comes to paying attention to themselves.
The course was conceived by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to launch the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the day, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why don’t I know about it until now, in my last year?’
After her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year’s course for the first time explained to students how the basics of good sleeping habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university opted to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, students see the picture of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
Then, using a map of the university campus with interactive symbols, they are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this – just like you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of “pushing a night shift” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Ensuring enough good sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into hunger mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, taking one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study program before starting their studies at the competitive university.
According to the recommendation of Professor Czeisler, students should prepare a wake-up alarm for bedtime and wake-up time, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emanates from electronic screens and LED lights, which can get the circadian rhythm off the clock, leading to problems with falling asleep.
