New Cancer Vaccine May Teach the Immune System to “See” Degenerate Cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “see” and destroy decayed cells.
The vaccine teaches the immune system to detect decayed cells during treatment.
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient that are altered in the laboratory.
These cells can “see” a common protein of many cancers and are then injected again.
A test vaccine shows promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
The ovarian cancer of a woman treated with the vaccine that teaches the immune system to detect decayed cells disappeared for more than 18 months.
In the method, immune cells are taken from a patient, which are modified in the laboratory so that they can "see" the protein HER2 common to many cancers, and then the cells are injected again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our findings suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
