National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research is being carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands to show how bats use the landscape in their food hunt.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insight into the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will track down dwarf and mosquito bat mice, as well as the brown long-eared and water bat mice in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
During a noise analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and determines which species is doing what.
A map and report of the habitat is then drawn up to provide a detailed picture of their behavior at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This data will help to identify the benefits of habitat management measures, such as meadow creation, and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
The bat stocks in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or even attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo tracking to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the topic of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly carry out investigations, sleeping place inspections and sometimes rescue measures.
The organization has even established Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s 10 bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for her.
“Here in Threave we have a great area for bats,” he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t yet know about bats, so we’re doing this work here and on other goods that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable.”
He stresses the importance of excluding bats before maintenance work in the goods, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and wipe out the entire population on site.
Bats are under protection and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: “We still have to learn a lot about bats and many of our species do not know what their populations are.”
