Fisheries and agriculture are the main sources of income for the Central Sulawesi economy, especially the Donggala coastal region.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been victims of earthquakes and tsunamis several times over the past 100 years, according to Indonesia’s Civil Protection Agency.
In 1938, more than 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
West Donggala was hit in 1996 by a tsunami that killed nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic Pacific ring of fire, and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in northern Sumatra on December 26 triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people in the coastal areas of the Indian Ocean, nearly half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of severe earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
Hundreds of people died on the Nias islands off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-strong earthquake rocked southern Java, Indonesia’s most populous island, triggering a tsunami that hit the south coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake of 7.6 hit the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake of 7.5 rocked one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of up to 10 meters high, destroying dozens of villages and claiming about 300 lives.
2016: A slight earthquake shook the governing district of Pidie Jaya in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people were reminded of the destruction of the deadly earthquake and tsunamis of 2004.
