Europe made a victory at the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National near Paris.
The U.S. has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won back the crown after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over most of the tournament, lowered his tee on the 16th track (par 3) in the water and lost to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in Team Europe, Thorbjørn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the best ranking in the world, Dustin Johnson, lost 2-1 to the Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spaniard Sergio Garcia, a veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I’m so happy to win the cup back.
It’s about the team and I’m happy to have made a contribution,” said the emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the torch to his compatriot John Rahm, who won against the American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday 2:1 in the singles matches.
“I’m so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, whom I’ve watched on TV since I was a child,” said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four of his games in France and now has a Ryder Cup record of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 important titles and is only surpassed by Jack Nicklaus.
The USA team had trouble finding the fairways all weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who made high-profile performances throughout the tournament.
U.S. Captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of the guys, they’ve fought.
There was a time this morning when we put pressure on Europe.
We didn't do anything about it.
Hat off for Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players performed well.
We will regroup, I will talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup committee and we will look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I am proud to be their captain.
You have to take your hat off.
We have been defeated.”
Update on red tide: concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are declining
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts, more varied flowering conditions are recorded, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae flower extends about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee District.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough district, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the past week, average concentrations in or off the coast of the Pinellas district have been reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Manatee district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Charlotte district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Lee district and low concentrations in the Collier district.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In Northwest Florida, no new respiratory problems have been reported over the past week.
